Comment: The KLF, founded by Bill Drummond and Jimmy Cauty, were one of the most unpredictable forces in late‚Äë80s and early‚Äë90s music. They pioneered ambient house with *Chill Out* (1990) and conquered the charts with *The White Room* (1991), producing global hits like ‚Äú3 a.m. Eternal,‚Äù ‚ÄúLast Train to Trancentral,‚Äù and ‚ÄúJustified & Ancient.‚Äù Their career was marked by anarchic gestures: in 1987 they clashed with ABBA over unauthorized samples and burned unsold records in a Swedish field; in 1992 they staged a notorious BRIT Awards performance with Extreme Noise Terror, firing blanks into the audience and leaving a dead sheep at the afterparty; and in 1994, as the K Foundation, they burned ¬£1 million in cash on the Isle of Jura. Shortly after the BRITs they deleted their back catalogue and retired. In just a few years they fused rave culture, pop stardom, and conceptual art, leaving behind a story that is both commercially dominant and astonishingly self‚Äëdestructive.
